            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this LBTT calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool estimates Land and Buildings Transaction Tax (LBTT)
                for property purchases in Scotland. It supports:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Standard <strong>residential</strong> purchases</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>First-time buyer</strong> relief (where eligible)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Additional Dwelling Supplement (ADS)</strong> for
                  second homes and buy-to-lets
                </li>
                <li><strong>Non-residential</strong> and mixed-use property</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                LBTT is calculated on a <strong>slice</strong> basis: different
                portions of the price fall into different bands and are taxed at
                different rates. The calculator applies the relevant bands and
                rates to each slice and sums the results.
              </p>

              <h3>Current LBTT bands and rates (illustrative)</h3>
              <p><strong>Residential property (standard buyer)</strong></p>
              <ul>
                <li>£0 – £145,000: 0%</li>
                <li>£145,001 – £250,000: 2%</li>
                <li>£250,001 – £325,000: 5%</li>
                <li>£325,001 – £750,000: 10%</li>
                <li>Over £750,000: 12%</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                <strong>First-time buyer relief</strong> typically increases the
                nil-rate threshold (for eligible buyers purchasing a main
                residence). The calculator models this by extending the 0% band;
                always confirm the exact threshold and conditions with Revenue
                Scotland.
              </p>

              <p><strong>Non-residential and mixed-use property</strong></p>
              <ul>
                <li>£0 – £150,000: 0%</li>
                <li>£150,001 – £250,000: 1%</li>
                <li>Over £250,000: 5%</li>
              </ul>

              <p><strong>Additional Dwelling Supplement (ADS)</strong></p>
              <p>
                ADS is an extra percentage charge on the
                <strong>full purchase price</strong> of most additional
                residential properties (for example, second homes and
                buy-to-lets). The exact ADS rate is set by the Scottish
                Government and can change, so always check the current rate on
                the official Revenue Scotland website.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Slice-based LBTT formula</p>
                <p>
                  For each band <code>i</code> with lower limit \(L_i\), upper
                  limit \(U_i\) and rate \(r_i\):
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Tax}_i = \max\big(0, \min(P, U_i) - L_i\big) \times
                  r_i \]
                </p>
                <p>where \(P\) is the purchase price. Total LBTT is:</p>
                <p>\[ \text{LBTT} = \sum_i \text{Tax}_i \]</p>
              </div>

              <h2>Worked examples</h2>

              <h3>
                Example 1 – £200,000 residential purchase (standard buyer, no
                ADS)
              </h3>
              <ul>
                <li>£0 – £145,000 at 0% → £0</li>
                <li>£145,001 – £200,000 (i.e. £55,000) at 2% → £1,100</li>
              </ul>
              <p><strong>LBTT due: £1,100</strong> (no ADS).</p>

              <h3>Example 2 – £300,000 residential purchase with ADS</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>LBTT (standard bands) calculated slice by slice</li>
                <li>
                  ADS charged on the full £300,000 at the current ADS rate
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator will show both the core LBTT and the ADS
                separately, plus the combined total.
              </p>

              <h2>Important notes and disclaimer</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>LBTT rules, bands and rates change over time.</li>
                <li>
                  Eligibility for first-time buyer relief and ADS refunds
                  depends on your specific circumstances.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Leases and complex commercial transactions may use different
                  rules.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This calculator is for
                <strong>guidance and education only</strong>. It does not
                replace the official Revenue Scotland calculator and is not
                legal, tax or financial advice. Always confirm figures with
                Revenue Scotland, the Scottish Government guidance, Registers of
                Scotland, or a qualified solicitor or tax adviser before
                committing to a transaction.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions about LBTT</h2>

              <h3>
                Do I pay LBTT on the whole price or just the part above the
                threshold?
              </h3>
              <p>
                LBTT is <strong>not</strong> a “cliff-edge” tax. Only the
                portion of the price that falls within each band is taxed at
                that band’s rate. The calculator’s band breakdown table shows
                exactly how much of your price falls into each band.
              </p>

              <h3>When is LBTT payable?</h3>
              <p>
                LBTT is normally due within a short period after the effective
                date of the transaction (usually completion). Your solicitor
                will usually submit the LBTT return and arrange payment on your
                behalf. Late filing or payment can result in penalties and
                interest.
              </p>

              <h3>What counts as a non-residential or mixed-use property?</h3>
              <p>
                Non-residential property includes commercial premises (such as
                shops, offices and industrial units), agricultural land and some
                other land transactions. Mixed-use property includes any
                transaction that combines residential and non-residential
                elements (for example, a flat above a shop). These use the
                non-residential LBTT bands.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I reclaim ADS if I sell my previous main residence?</h3>
              <p>
                In some cases, yes. If you pay ADS when buying a new main
                residence while still owning your previous one, you may be able
                to reclaim ADS if you sell the previous main residence within a
                specified time window. The rules are detailed and time-limited,
                so always check the latest guidance and speak to your solicitor.
              </p>
